The upcoming '''''Columbia'' class''' (formerly known as the '''''Ohio'' Replacement Submarine''' and '''SSBN-X Future Follow-on Submarine''') are [[Nuclear submarine|nuclear]]-powered [[ballistic missile submarine]]s of the [[United States Navy]], designed to replace the {{sclass|Ohio|submarine|4}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/systems/ssbn-x.htm |title=SSBN-X Future Follow-on Submarine |date=24 July 2011 |website=GlobalSecurity.org |access-date=24 July 2011}}</ref> Construction of the first vessel began on 1 October 2020,<ref name= "Build1">{{Cite web|url=https://news.usni.org/2019/05/08/navy-uss-columbia-will-have-most-completed-design-ever-at-official-construction-start|title=Navy: USS Columbia Will Have Most Complete Design Ever at Official Construction Start |work=USNI News |last=Eckstein |first=Megan |date=8 May 2019 |access-date=8 July 2025}}</ref> and is scheduled to enter service in 2031.<ref name=":0">{{cite web |url=https://media.defense.gov/2018/Feb/02/2001872886/-1/-1/1/2018-NUCLEAR-POSTURE-REVIEW-FINAL-REPORT.PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202200026/https://media.defense.gov/2018/Feb/02/2001872886/-1/-1/1/2018-NUCLEAR-POSTURE-REVIEW-FINAL-REPORT.PDF |archive-date=2 February 2018 |title=Nuclear Posture Review Final Report |date=2018 |publisher=Office of the Secretary of Defense}}</ref><ref name="senedia.org">{{cite web |url=http://www.senedia.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Ohio-Replacement-Program-Defense-Innovation-Days-5-Sep-2014-Final.pdf |title=SENEDIA Defense Innovation Days |date=5 September 2014 |website=Senedia.org |access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Rebecca |last=Rebarich |url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=42793 |title=1,000 Trident Patrols: SSBNs the Cornerstone of Strategic Deterrence |publisher=United States Navy |access-date=20 August 2016}}{{dead link|date=April 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

On 3 June 2022, the Navy announced that the lead vessel of the class will be named {{USS|District of Columbia|SSBN-826}}, because there is already an [[attack submarine]] named {{USS|Columbia|SSN-771}}.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Burgess |first=Richard R. |date=2022-06-06 |title=DC Congresswoman Pushes DC Statehood at Keel-Laying for Navy Submarine |url=https://seapowermagazine.org/dc-congresswoman-pushes-dc-statehood-at-keel-laying-for-navy-submarine/ |access-date=2024-04-10 |website=Seapower |language=en-US}}</ref> Nevertheless, the Navy has since continued to refer to the class as ''Columbia''.<ref>{{Cite web |title=SECNAV Names SSBN 826 USS District of Columbia |url=https://www.navy.mil/Press-Office/News-Stories/Article/3052632/secnav-names-ssbn-826-uss-district-of-columbia/ |access-date=2022-06-04 |date=3 June 2024 |publisher=United States Navy |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220603214005/https://www.navy.mil/Press-Office/News-Stories/Article/3052632/secnav-names-ssbn-826-uss-district-of-columbia/ |archive-date=3 June 2022 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=CNO Visits Philadelphia for Submarine and Shipbuilding Updates |url=https://www.navy.mil/Press-Office/Press-Releases/display-pressreleases/Article/3685879/cno-visits-philadelphia-for-submarine-and-shipbuilding-updates/https://www.navy.mil/Press-Office/Press-Releases/display-pressreleases/Article/3685879/cno-visits-philadelphia-for-submarine-and-shipbuilding-updates/ |access-date=2024-04-10 |publisher=United States Navy |language=en-US}}{{dead link|date=April 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

==Overview==
The ''Columbia'' class is to replace the ''Ohio'' class of ballistic missile submarines, whose remaining boats are to be decommissioned, one per year, beginning in 2028.{{cn|date=January 2024}} The ''Columbia'' class will take over the role of submarine presence in the United States' [[Nuclear triad|strategic nuclear force]].<ref name= "FAS01"/>

[[Electric Boat]] designed the new class with help from [[Newport News Shipbuilding]]. A total of twelve submarines are planned,<ref name= "USNI12">{{cite web |url=https://news.usni.org/2018/11/08/columbia-class-program-upping-oversight-of-vendors-components-to-stave-off-further-delays |title=Columbia-class Program Upping Oversight of Vendors, Components to Stave Off Further Delays |work=USNI News |last=Eckstein |first=Megan |date=8 November 2018 |access-date=9 November 2018}}</ref> and construction of the lead boat began in 2021. Each submarine will have sixteen missile tubes, each carrying one [[UGM-133 Trident II]] D5LE missile.{{citation needed|date=October 2025}} (The ninth and later ''Columbia''s are to receive the upgraded D5LE2s.)<ref name=NextSub>{{Cite web|title=Next Sub-Launched Ballistic Missile 'Won't Be Completely New'|url=https://seapowermagazine.org/next-sub-launched-ballistic-missile-wont-be-completely-new/|last1=Burgess|first1=Richard R.|date=2018-11-08|website=Seapower|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-22}}</ref><ref name="Burgess 2021">{{cite web | last=Burgess | first=Richard R. | title=Navy's SSP Admiral: New Missile Planned for Introduction on 9th Columbia SSBN | website=Seapower | date=10 June 2021 | url=https://seapowermagazine.org/navys-ssp-admiral-new-missile-planned-for-introduction-on-9th-columbia-ssbn/ | access-date=9 November 2022}}</ref> The submarines will be {{convert|560|ft|m|1}} long and {{convert|43|ft|m|1}} in diameter, as long as the ''Ohio''-class design, and {{convert|1|ft|cm|0|sp=us}} larger in diameter.<ref name= "FAS01"/>

To determine how many submarines would be needed for the US strategic nuclear force, Navy planners calculated how many missiles would be needed at sea and on station at any given time, how many each submarine should carry, and the likelihood that a submarine will remain undiscovered by the enemy and be able to launch. They also explored how required maintenance would affect availability.<ref name="kristensen1">{{cite web |first=Hans M. |last=Kristensen |url=http://blogs.fas.org/security/2013/07/ssbnx-numbers/ |title=SSBNX Under Pressure: Submarine Chief Says Navy Can't Reduce |website=FAS Strategic Security Blog |publisher=[[Federation of American Scientists]] |date=24 July 2013 |access-date=17 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906101555/http://blogs.fas.org/security/2013/07/ssbnx-numbers/ |archive-date=6 September 2013 }}</ref> Cost-reduction studies explored design and construction possibilities, including adding missile tubes to the design of the {{sclass|Virginia|submarine|0}} [[attack submarine]], building ''Ohio-''class replacement submarines using updated ''Ohio''-class designs, and developing an entirely new ''Ohio'' Replacement Submarine design.<ref name= "FAS01"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Kelly |first=Jason |url=http://navylive.dodlive.mil/2013/06/26/facts-we-can-agree-upon-about-design-of-ohio-replacement-ssbn/ |title=Facts We Can Agree Upon About Design of Ohio Replacement SSBN |publisher=Navylive.dodlive.mil |access-date=17 August 2013}}</ref>

[[File:SSBN-X.jpg|thumb|2012 artist's conception of the Ohio Replacement Submarine]]
The Navy concluded that a new design would be the least expensive option that could meet all of the technical requirements.<ref name="kristensen1"/> For example, while the modified ''Virginia''-class and updated ''Ohio''-class design options would have required an expensive mid-life refueling,<ref name= "FAS01"/> each ''Columbia''-class nuclear core will last as long as the submarine is in service.<ref name="arm">{{cite web |url=http://www.armscontrol.org/factsheets/USNuclearModernization |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100405072941/https://www.armscontrol.org/factsheets/USNuclearModernization |archive-date=5 April 2010 |title=U.S. Nuclear Modernization Programs |publisher=[[Arms Control Association]] |access-date=1 November 2012}}</ref><ref name="defensemedianetwork1">{{cite web |url=http://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/ohio-class-replacement-will-carry-%e2%80%9cre-packaged-and-re-hosted%e2%80%9d-weapons-system/ |title=Ohio-class Replacement Will Carry "Re-packaged and Re-hosted" Weapons System |publisher=Defense Media Network |date=4 February 2011 |access-date=6 February 2013}}</ref>

The design and technology development of the ''Columbia'' class is projected to cost $4.2 billion (fiscal 2010 dollars), with technology and components from the ''Ohio'' and ''Virginia'' classes included where possible to save money.{{Citation needed|date=October 2025}} The cost to build ''District of'' ''Columbia'', the [[Lead ship|lead boat]] of the class, will be an estimated $6.2 billion (fiscal 2010 dollars).<ref name= "FAS01"/> The Navy has a goal of reducing the average cost of the remaining eleven planned hulls in the class to $4.9 billion each (fiscal 2010 dollars).<ref name=arm /> The total lifecycle cost of the entire class is estimated at $347 billion.<ref name=arm /> The high cost of the submarines is expected to cut deeply into Navy shipbuilding.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Gopal |last1=Ratnam |first2=Tony |last2=Capaccio |title=U.S. Navy Sees 20-Year, $333 Billion Plan Missing Ship Goals |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-09/u-s-navy-sees-20-year-333-billion-plan-missing-ship-goals.html |work=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=9 March 2011 |access-date=9 March 2011}}</ref>

In April 2014, the Navy completed a 300-page specification report for the ''Ohio'' Replacement Program submarines. There are 159 specifications including weapons, escape routes, fluid systems, hatches, doors, seawater systems, and a set length of {{Convert|560|ft|m|abbr=on}}, partly to allow for sufficient volume inside the pressure hull.<ref name="dodbuzz8april14"/>

In March 2016, the US Navy chose General Dynamics Electric Boat as the prime contractor and lead design yard.<ref>{{cite web |author=Grace Jean |url=http://www.janes.com/article/59110/usn-taps-general-dynamics-electric-boat-as-prime-contractor-for-ohio-replacement-programme |title=USN taps General Dynamics Electric Boat as prime contractor for Ohio Replacement Programme |website= IHS Jane's 360, Janes.com |date=30 March 2016 |access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Electric Boat, which built all eighteen ''Ohio-class'' submarines,<ref>{{cite web |date=15 June 2011 |title=SSBN / SSGN Ohio Class Submarine |url=http://www.naval-technology.com/projects/ohio/ |access-date=20 August 2016 |website=Naval Technology}}</ref> will do most of the work on all twelve ''Columbia'' boats, including final assembly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2016/03/ohio-replacement-plan-is-good-news-for-electronic-boat/ |title=Ohio Replacement Plan Is Good News For Electric Boat |website=Breaking Defense |date=29 March 2016 |access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> Huntington Ingalls Industries' Newport News Shipbuilding will serve as the main subcontractor, participating in the design and construction and doing 22 to 23 percent of the work.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pilotonline.com/business/defense-shipyards/newport-news-shipbuilding-s-share-of-virginia-class-submarine-deliveries/article_b6e6e27d-f180-5186-ba0b-ab3eef76ffcf.html |title=Newport News Shipbuilding's share of Virginia-class submarine deliveries to grow &#124; Defense & Shipyards |website=Pilotonline.com |date=29 March 2016 |access-date=20 August 2016 |archive-date=4 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504152928/http://pilotonline.com/business/defense-shipyards/newport-news-shipbuilding-s-share-of-virginia-class-submarine-deliveries/article_b6e6e27d-f180-5186-ba0b-ab3eef76ffcf.html }}</ref>

In late 2016, some 3,000 Electric Boat employees were involved in the detailed-design phase of the program<ref>{{cite news |last=Bergman |first=Julia |title=Navy contracts mean Electric Boat will hire 14,000 over next 13 years |url=http://www.theday.com/military/20161210/navy-contracts-mean-electric-boat-will-hire-14000-over-next-13-years |newspaper=The Day |date=10 December 2016 |url-access=limited |archive-date=12 November 2017 |access-date=15 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112072143/http://www.theday.com/military/20161210/navy-contracts-mean-electric-boat-will-hire-14000-over-next-13-years |url-status=dead }}</ref> and the procurement of the first submarine was scheduled for 2021.<ref name= "FAS01">{{cite web |first=Ronald |last=O'Rourke |title=Navy Navy SSBN(X) Ballistic Missile Submarine Program: Background and Issues for Congress |url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/weapons/R41129.pdf |id=R41129 |publisher=[[Congressional Research Service]] |date=17 September 2017 |access-date=23 September 2017 |via=Federation of American Scientists |archive-date=4 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504225457/http://www.fas.org/sgp/crs/weapons/R41129.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref> Completion of the first submarine was scheduled for 2030, followed by its entry into service in 2031. All twelve submarines are expected to be completed by 2042 and remain in service until 2085.<ref name= "FAS01"/><ref name="dodbuzz8april14">{{cite web |author=Kris Osborn |url=http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/04/08/navy-finishes-blueprints-for-future-nuclear-sub/ |title=Navy Finishes Specs for Future Nuclear Sub |website=Dodbuzz.com |date=8 April 2014 |access-date=20 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515170309/http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/04/08/navy-finishes-blueprints-for-future-nuclear-sub/ |archive-date=15 May 2016 }}</ref>

On 28 July 2016, it was reported that the first submarine of the class will be named ''Columbia'', to commemorate the [[District of Columbia]], the capital of the United States.<ref>{{cite web |author=Sam LaGrone |url=https://news.usni.org/2016/07/28/ohio-replacement-sub-class-named-d-c |title=New U.S. Navy Nuclear Sub Class to Be Named for D.C.|website=News.usni.org |date=28 July 2016 |access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref> The ''Columbia'' class was officially designated on 14 December 2016 by Secretary of the Navy [[Ray Mabus]], and the lead submarine will be {{USS|District of Columbia|SSBN-826}}.<ref>[https://news.usni.org/2016/12/13/secnav-mabus-to-officially-designate-first-orp-boat-uss-district-of-columbia-ssbn-826 "SECNAV Mabus to Officially Designate First ORP Boat USS ''Columbia'' (SSBN-826)"]. USNI News, 13 December 2016.</ref> The Navy wanted to procure the first ''Columbia''-class boat in FY2021.<ref>[https://news.usni.org/2020/05/19/report-columbia-class-nuclear-ballistic-missile-submarine-program "Report on the Columbia-class Nuclear Ballistic Missile Submarine Program"]. ''USNI News'', 20 May 2020.</ref>

On 28 October 2020, US Navy Secretary [[Kenneth J. Braithwaite]] announced that the second submarine would be named {{USS|Wisconsin|SSBN-827}}, after the [[Wisconsin|US state]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Santos|first=Babs|date=October 29, 2020|title=U.S. Navy to name submarine after Wisconsin|publisher=[[WLUK-TV]]|url=https://fox11online.com/news/state/us-navy-to-name-submarine-after-wisconsin|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201105155646/https://fox11online.com/news/state/us-navy-to-name-submarine-after-wisconsin|archive-date=November 5, 2020}}</ref>

On 7 June 2021, the US Navy budget office announced that the total cost for ''District of Columbia'' would reach $15.03 billion, which includes planning costs for the entire program.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usni.org/2021/06/07/cost-estimates-for-lead-boat-in-columbia-class-program-grow-by-637m#:~:text=The%20estimated%20price%20for%20the,documents%20released%20late%20last%20week |title=Cost Estimates for Lead Boat in Columbia-class Program Grow by $637M|website=USNI News|date=7 June 2021|access-date=18 August 2021}}</ref> As of April 2023, the estimated construction cost of the twelve-boat program is $132 billion. Securing the supply chain and maintaining a skilled labor force are two major challenges for the program.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Capaccio |first=Anthony |date=April 12, 2023 |title=Pentagon Muzzles GAO's Doubts About Nuclear-Armed Submarine's Schedule |work=Bloomberg |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-12/pentagon-muzzles-gao-s-doubts-about-nuclear-armed-submarine-s-schedule |access-date=May 26, 2023 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20230414140655/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-04-12/pentagon-muzzles-gao-s-doubts-about-nuclear-armed-submarine-s-schedule?leadSource=uverify%20wall |archive-date=April 14, 2023}}</ref>

==General characteristics==
[[File:Columbia-class submarine, NAVSEA concept.png|thumb|right|Graphic artist concept, 2012]]

Although still evolving, the following are some of the characteristics for the SSBN(X) design:<ref name="senedia.org"/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20141213041334/http://www.ssbn.pl/files/OHIO_Replacement_Program_Naval_Submarine_League.pdf OHIO Replacement Program Naval Submarine League ssbn.pl]</ref>
* Expected 42-year service life, including 124 deterrent patrols.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://defensetech.org/2013/10/24/ohio-replacement-submarine-starts-early-construction/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025012542/http://defensetech.org/2013/10/24/ohio-replacement-submarine-starts-early-construction/ |url-status=usurped |archive-date=25 October 2013 |title=Ohio Replacement Submarine Starts Early Construction|date=24 October 2013}}</ref>
* [[S1B reactor|Nuclear fuel core]] that will power the submarine for its entire expected service life, unlike the ''Ohio''-class submarines, which require a mid-life nuclear refueling.<ref name="defensemedianetwork1"/>
* Missile launch tubes that are the same size as those of the ''Ohio'' class, with a diameter of {{convert|87|in}} and a height sufficient to accommodate a D-5 Trident II missile.
* Beam at least as great as the {{convert|42|ft|adj=on}} beam of the ''Ohio''-class submarines
* 16 missile launch tubes instead of 24 missile launch tubes on ''Ohio''-class submarines.<ref name= "FAS01"/><ref name="did">{{cite news |url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/CMC-contract-to-Define-Future-SSBN-Launchers-for-UK-USA-05221/ |title=CMC Program to Define Future SSBN Launchers for UK, USA|work=Defense Industry Daily|date=25 November 2012|access-date=3 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbo.gov/sites/default/files/cbofiles/attachments/07-25-12-NavyShipbuilding_0.pdf |title=An Analysis of the Navy's Fiscal Year 2013 Shipbuilding Plan|publisher=[[Congressional Budget Office]]|access-date=3 December 2012}}</ref><ref name="usni">{{cite news |url=http://news.usni.org/news-analysis/news/ohio-class-replacement-details |title=Ohio-class Replacement Details|work=US Naval Institute|date=1 November 2012|access-date=3 December 2012}}</ref>
* Although the SSBN(X) is to have fewer launch tubes than the ''Ohio''-class submarine, SSBN(X) is expected to have a submerged displacement about the same as that of ''Ohio''-class submarines

The US Navy has also said that "owing to the unique demands of strategic relevance, SSBN(X)s must be fitted with the most up-to-date capabilities and stealth to ensure they are survivable throughout their full 40-year life span."<ref name= "FAS01"/>

In November 2012, the US Naval Institute, citing [[Naval Sea Systems Command]], revealed additional design information:<ref name="usni" />
* X-shaped stern control surfaces (hydroplanes)
* Sail-mounted dive planes
* Electric drive
* Off-the-shelf equipment developed for previous submarine designs (''Virginia''-class SSNs), including a [[pump-jet]] propulsor, [[anechoic tile|anechoic coating]] and a Large Aperture Bow (LAB) sonar system.

[[File:Ohio Replacement Submarine cutaway 2014 Sea, Air, and Space Symposium.png|thumb|Cutaway image, 2014]]
The ''Columbia''-class submarine may also be equipped with a Submarine Warfare Federated Tactical System (SWFTS), a cluster of systems that integrate sonar, optical imaging, weapons control etc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.navsea.navy.mil/OnWatch2011/ohioclass.html|title=On Watch 2011|publisher=Navsea.navy.mil|access-date=6 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130303015649/http://www.navsea.navy.mil/OnWatch2011/ohioclass.html|archive-date=3 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Keller |first=John |url=http://www.militaryaerospace.com/articles/2012/04/lockheed-martin-to-adapt-submarine-combat-systems-for-network-centric-warfare-operations-at-sea.html |title=Lockheed Martin to adapt submarine combat systems for network-centric warfare operations at sea |publisher= Military & Aerospace Electronics, Militaryaerospace.com |date=15 April 2012 |access-date=2 February 2014}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20091030142545/http://www.navsea.navy.mil/Newswire2009/JUN18-04.aspx NAVSEA News]. navy.mil</ref>

===Propulsion===
{{main|Integrated electric propulsion}}

In a bid to reduce life-cycle cost and [[acoustic signature]],<ref>{{cite web |date=6 July 2006 |title=Propulsion Systems for Navy Ships and Submarines |url=http://www.gao.gov/assets/100/94295.pdf |website=[[Government Accounting Office]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.nap.edu/openbook.php?record_id=5863&page=230 |title=Technology for the United States Navy and Marine Corps, 2000–2035 Becoming a 21st-Century Force: Volume 2: Technology |date=1 June 2003 |publisher=Nap.edu |isbn=978-0-309-05897-1 |doi=10.17226/5863 |access-date=30 May 2013}}</ref> ''Columbia'' is to run on electric drive—that is, it will use an electric motor to turn its propellers instead of the reduction gearing and mechanical drive systems used on earlier nuclear-powered submarines.<ref name="autogeneratedmil">{{cite web |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/usw/issue_9/power_system.html |title=An Integrated Electric Power System: the Next Step |publisher=Navy.mil |access-date=6 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121128004930/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/usw/issue_9/power_system.html |archive-date=28 November 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/going-electric/ |title=Going Electric |publisher=Defense Media Network |date=14 June 2010 |access-date=6 February 2013}}</ref> It will retain the nuclear reactor and [[steam turbine]]s typical of US Navy submarines. In such systems, the nuclear reactor heats water to steam, the turbines convert the heat in the steam into mechanical energy, and the generators convert that mechanical energy into electrical energy<ref>{{cite web |last=Bowman (ADM USN, Director Naval Nuclear Propulsion) |first=Frank "Skip" |date=Fall 2000 |title=Undersea Warfare Fall 2000, Vol 3, No 1 - An Integrated Power System: The Next Step |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/usw/issue_9/power_system.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120805072635/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/usw/issue_9/power_system.html |archive-date=5 August 2012 }}</ref> for use by the propulsion motors and other onboard systems.<ref name="northropgrumman.com" /><ref>{{cite web |author=Kris Osborn |title=Ohio Replacement Subs To Shift To Electric Drive |url=http://defensetech.org/2013/09/27/ohio-class-subs-to-shift-to-electric-drive/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927232209/http://defensetech.org/2013/09/27/ohio-class-subs-to-shift-to-electric-drive/ |url-status=usurped |archive-date=27 September 2013 |access-date=20 August 2016 |website=Defensetech.org}}</ref>

[[Turbo-electric]] drives were successfully used on US battleships and aircraft carriers in the first half of the 20th century,<ref>{{cite web |author=Tony DiGiulian |url=http://www.navweaps.com/index_tech/tech-038.htm |title=Turboelectric Drive in American Capital Ships |publisher=Navweaps.com |access-date=6 February 2013}}</ref> and on the small nuclear-powered submarine {{USS|Tullibee|SSN-597|6}} in the late 1950s.<ref>{{cite web |author=Paul Lambert |url=http://www.usstullibee.com/tullibeehistory.html |title=USS Tullibee – History |website=USS Tullibee SSN 597 |access-date=6 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517121715/http://www.usstullibee.com/tullibeehistory.html |archive-date=17 May 2014 }}</ref> Another larger nuclear-powered submarine, {{USS|Glenard P. Lipscomb|SSN-685|6}}, was equipped with a turboelectric drive but proved to be underpowered, unreliable, and maintenance-hungry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/history/subhistory3.html |title=Submarine Technology thru the Years |publisher=Navy.mil |date=19 July 1997 |access-date=6 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212063112/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/history/subhistory3.html |archive-date=12 February 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |author=Sam LaGrone |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/01/secret-sub-design/ |title=Secret Nuclear Redesign Will Keep U.S. Subs Running Silently for 50 Years |magazine=Wired |publisher=Danger Room, Wired.com |date=28 March 2013 |access-date=30 May 2013}}</ref> {{As of|2013}}, the only operational turboelectric-powered subs were the French Navy's {{sclass|Triomphant|submarine|2}}s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naval-technology.com/projects/triomphant/ |title=SSBN Triomphant Class |publisher=Naval Technology |date=15 June 2011 |access-date=6 February 2013}}</ref>

In 2014, [[Northrop Grumman]] was chosen as the prime designer and manufacturer of ''Columbia''{{'}}s turbine generator units.<ref name="northropgrumman.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.northropgrumman.com/MediaResources/Pages/NewsArticle.aspx?art=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.globenewswire.com%2Fnewsarchive%2Fnoc%2Fpress%2Fxml%2Fnitf.html%3Fd%3D10083180 |title=News |work=Northrop Grumman |access-date=8 June 2014 |archive-date=10 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110080441/http://www.northropgrumman.com/MediaResources/Pages/NewsArticle.aspx?art=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.globenewswire.com%2Fnewsarchive%2Fnoc%2Fpress%2Fxml%2Fnitf.html%3Fd%3D10083180 |url-status=dead }}</ref> That same year [[Leonardo DRS]] was selected as the main propulsion motor and propulsion motor drive provider. The lead ship motor was delivered to Electric Boat in August 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 31, 2022 |title=Leonardo DRS Delivers Electric Propulsion Equipment for 1st Columbia Submarine |url=https://www.navalnews.com/naval-news/2022/08/leonardo-drs-delivers-electric-propulsion-equipment-for-1st-columbia-submarine/ |access-date=2022-12-04 |website=Naval News |language=en}}</ref>

Various types of electric motors have and are being developed for military and non-military vessels.<ref name="alexandria1">{{cite web |url=http://alexandria.tue.nl/SAI/openaccess/750674.pdf |title=Concept study of 20 MW highspeed permanent magnet synchronous motor for marine propulsion |last=Bogomolov |first=M.D. |date=22 January 2013 |publisher=[[Eindhoven University of Technology]]}}</ref> Types being considered for future US submarines include permanent magnet motors (PMM) being developed by [[General Dynamics]] and Newport News Shipbuilding, and high-temperature superconducting synchronous motors, being developed by American Superconductors and [[General Atomics]].<ref name="alexandria1" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/weapons/RL33360.pdf |title=Navy Ship Propulsion Technologies: Options for Reducing Oil Use — Background for Congress |date=11 December 2006 |first=Ronald |last=O'Rourke |website=[[Federation of American Scientists]] |id=RL33360 |access-date=25 November 2015 |archive-date=15 May 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060515035552/http://www.fas.org/sgp/crs/weapons/RL33360.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Sonal Patel |url=http://www.powermag.com/issues/departments/global_monitor/Superconductor-Motor-for-Navy-Passes-Full-Power-Test_1759.html |title=Superconductor Motor for Navy Passes Full-Power Test :: POWER Magazine |publisher=Powermag.com |date=1 March 2009 |access-date=30 May 2013 |archive-date=19 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419215043/http://www.powermag.com/issues/departments/global_monitor/Superconductor-Motor-for-Navy-Passes-Full-Power-Test_1759.html }}</ref> More recent{{when|date=January 2025}} data shows that the US Navy appears to be focusing on permanent-magnet, radial-gap electric propulsion motors.{{citation needed|date=January 2025}} The {{sclass|Zumwalt|destroyer|1}} design switched from PMM to an advanced induction motor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://defense.about.com/od/Navy/a/Ddg-1000-Zumwalt-Class-Destroyer.htm |title=DDG-1000 Zumwalt Class Destroyer |publisher=Defense.about.com |date=1 November 2012 |access-date=6 February 2013 |archive-date=21 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130121131428/http://defense.about.com/od/Navy/a/Ddg-1000-Zumwalt-Class-Destroyer.htm }}</ref> In 2013, permanent magnet motors were tested on the [[Virginia-class submarine#History|Large Scale Vehicle II]] for possible application on late-production ''Virginia''-class submarines, as well as future submarines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/usw/issue_11/submarine_stealth.html |title=Small Subs Provide Big Payoffs for Submarine Stealth |publisher=Navy.mil |access-date=6 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313053142/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/usw/issue_11/submarine_stealth.html |archive-date=13 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Dan Petty |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/fact_display.asp?cid=4100&tid=700&ct=4 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050527203805/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/fact_display.asp?cid=4100&tid=700&ct=4 |archive-date=27 May 2005 |title=The US Navy – Fact File: Large Scale Vehicle – LSV 2 |publisher=Navy.mil |access-date=6 February 2013}}</ref> Siemens AG PMMs are used on [[Type 212 submarine]]s in service with the [[German Navy|German]] and [[Italian Navy|Italian]] navies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.industry.usa.siemens.com/verticals/us/en/marine-shipbuilding/brochures/Documents/SINAVY-Permasyn-en.pdf |title=SINAVY CIS Permasyn |website=Siemens |year=2009 |access-date=30 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220073523/http://www.industry.usa.siemens.com/verticals/us/en/marine-shipbuilding/brochures/Documents/SINAVY-Permasyn-en.pdf |archive-date=20 February 2014}}</ref>

The [[Royal Navy]]'s {{sclass|Dreadnought|submarine|1}}, which is to replace the {{sclass|Vanguard|submarine|4}} of ballistic missile submarines, may have submarine shaftless drive (SSD) with an electric motor mounted outside the pressure hull.<ref name="harpoondatabases1">{{cite web |url=http://www.harpoondatabases.com/encyclopedia/Entry3128.aspx |title=SSBN "Strategic Successor Submarine" project |website=Harpoon Headquarters |access-date=17 August 2013}}</ref>{{unreliable source? |reason=User contributor site |date=August 2013}} SSD was evaluated by the US Navy, but it remains unknown whether the ''Columbia'' class will have it.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/products/janes/defence-security-report.aspx?id=1065928111 |title=Tango Bravo: breaking down barriers in submarine design |publisher=Janes.com |date=23 March 2007 |access-date=30 May 2013}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/tango-bravo-rd-project-to-drive-down-sub-size-0359/ |title=Tango Bravo R&D Project to Drive Down Sub Size |publisher=Defenseindustrydaily.com |access-date=30 May 2013}}</ref> On contemporary nuclear submarines, steam turbines are linked to reduction gears and a shaft rotating the propeller/pump-jet propulsor. With SSD, steam would drive electric turbogenerators, powered by steam turbines, that would be connected to a non-penetrating electric junction at the aft end of the pressure hull, with a watertight electric motor mounted externally, possibly an Integrated Motor Propulsor arrangement,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/usw/issue_14/torpedoes.html |title=Torpedoes and the Next Generation of Undersea Weapons |publisher=Navy.mil |access-date=1 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150420224306/http://www.navy.mil/navydata/cno/n87/usw/issue_14/torpedoes.html |archive-date=20 April 2015}}</ref> powering the pump-jet propulsor,<ref name="harpoondatabases1" /> although SSD concepts without pump-jet propulsors also exist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.mit.edu/2n/Abst-ExecSum/2006/Conversion/RIM%20ELECT%20DRI-INTER%20SUB.pdf |title=The Rim Electric Drive – Internal Submarine |first1=Dave |last1=Kuhn |first2=Joe |last2=Torrez |first3=William |last3=Fallier |publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |website=Naval Construction and Engineering |year=2006 |access-date=30 May 2013 |archive-date=4 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160804222116/http://web.mit.edu/2n/Abst-ExecSum/2006/Conversion/RIM%20ELECT%20DRI-INTER%20SUB.pdf }}</ref> In 2015, an ''Ohio-''Replacement scale model at the Navy League's 2015 Sea-Air-Space Exposition suggested that the sub would have a pump-jet propulsor visually similar to the one used on ''Virginia'' class<ref name="navyrecognition1">{{cite web |url=https://www.armyrecognition.com/archives/archives-naval-defense/naval-defense-2015/-gdeb-unveils-new-ohio-replacement-ssbn-x-detailed-model-at-sea-air-space-2015-exposition |title=GDEB Unveils New Ohio Replacement (SSBN-X) Detailed Model at Sea-Air-Space 2015 Exposition |website=Navyrecognition.com |date=14 April 2015 |access-date=20 August 2016}}</ref><ref name="usni" /> perhaps as part of the Navy's stated desire to reuse ''Virginia'' components to reduce risk and cost of construction.<ref name="navyrecognition1" /><ref name="FAS01" />

===Common missile compartment===
In December 2008, General Dynamics Electric Boat Corporation was selected to design the Common Missile Compartment (CMC) that will be used on the ''Ohio''-class successor.<ref name="did" /> In 2012, the US Navy announced plans for its SSBN(X) to share a CMC design with the Royal Navy's ''Dreadnought''-class ballistic missile submarine.<ref name= "FAS01"/> The CMC will house SLBMs in "quad packs".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=69425 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130626170707/http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=69425 |archive-date=26 June 2013 |title=Navy Signs Specification Document for the Ohio Replacement Submarine Program, Sets forth Critical Design Elements |website=Navy News Service |date=6 September 2012 |access-date=21 April 2013 |id=NNS120906-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Patani |first=Arif |url=http://navylive.dodlive.mil/2012/09/24/next-generation-ohio-class/ |title=Next Generation Ohio-Class |publisher=Navylive.dodlive.mil |date=24 September 2012 |access-date=21 April 2013}}</ref>

